### Inheritance

Inheritance allows a class (derived) to inherit properties and methods from another class (base). It promotes code reuse and establishes hierarchical relationships.

---

### Basic Syntax

```cpp
class Base {
  // Base class members
};

class Derived : accessSpecifier Base {
  // Derived class members
};
```

---

### Inheritance Example

```cpp
class Animal {
public:
  void eat() {
    cout << "Eating...";
  }
};

class Dog : public Animal {
public:
  void bark() {
    cout << "Barking...";
  }
};

Dog d;
d.eat();  // Inherited from Animal
d.bark(); // Own method
```

---

### Access Specifier Effects

| Base Member Access | Public Inheritance | Protected Inheritance | Private Inheritance |
|-------------------|-------------------|----------------------|--------------------|
| public | public | protected | private |
| protected | protected | protected | private |
| private | Not accessible | Not accessible | Not accessible |

---

### Types of Inheritance

| Type | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Single | One base, one derived |
| Multiple | Multiple bases, one derived |
| Multilevel | A -> B -> C |
| Hierarchical | One base, multiple derived |
| Hybrid | Combination of multiple types |

---

### Multiple Inheritance

```cpp
class Bird {
public:
  void fly() { cout << "Flying"; }
};

class Fish {
public:
  void swim() { cout << "Swimming"; }
};

class FlyingFish : public Bird, public Fish {
  // Inherits both fly() and swim()
};
```

---

> **Key Point:** Use `public` inheritance to model an "is-a" relationship. A derived class should be substitutable for its base class (Liskov Substitution Principle).

